'''Alexander Lévy''' ({{IPA-fr|le.vi}}; born 1 August 1990) is a French [[professional golfer]] who currently plays on the [[European Tour]].<ref name=ocr>{{cite news |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/levy-627562-tour-golf.html |title=Levy c'est grand |newspaper=Orange County Register |first=Matt |last=Hanlon |date=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=ETProfile>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/players/playerid=37791/index.html |title= European Tour - Player Profile |publisher=[[European Tour]] |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>

Lévy won the French Amateur Championship in 2009, and the French International Amateur Championship the next year.  Turning pro in 2011, his first wins of the European Tour came in 2014 at the [[Volvo China Open]] and the [[Portugal Masters]]. He won the 2016 [[Porsche European Open]], and the 2017 Volvo China Open. He won the [[Trophee Hassan II]] in 2018, he has won a title in each year since 2016 so far and rose to 47th in the world following his victory. At a nationwide level, only fellow countryman [[Thomas Levet]] is in possession of more titles on the [[European Tour]] (6), Levy currently trails Levet by one.

==Personal life==
Levy was born to French parents on 1 August 1990 in [[Orange, California]], and is Jewish.<ref name=ocr/><ref name=rKaplan>{{cite web |url=http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2014/04/29/fore/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140709114017/http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2014/04/29/fore/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=9 July 2014 |title=Fore |first=Ron |last=Kaplan |date=29 April 2014 }}</ref>[http://www.golf.com/tour-and-news/alcott-fleisher-pressel-dont-pass-over-jewish-golfers] His father (Philippe) and mother are pharmacists.<ref name=ocr/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/players/playerid=37791/bio/index.html |title=Alexander Levy biography |publisher=PGA European Tour}}</ref>

When he was four years old, his family moved to [[Bandol]], France, where he resides.<ref name=ocr/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/players/playerid=37791/bio/index.html |title=Alexander Levy biography |publisher=PGA European Tour |accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> At 14 years of age, he joined the French Federation of Golf's academy for secondary school.<ref name=ocr/> His nickname is El Toro.<ref name="golfchannel.com"/>

==Amateur career==
Lévy had a successful amateur career before turning professional, winning the French Amateur Championship in 2009 and the French International Amateur Championship the next year,<ref name=IMGProfile>{{cite web |url=http://www.imggolf.com/Our-Clients/Golfers/Alexander-Levy.aspx |title=IMG Golf - Player Profile |publisher=IMG Golf |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426232343/http://www.imggolf.com/Our-Clients/Golfers/Alexander-Levy.aspx |archive-date=2014-04-26 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> when he was also a member of the winning French team at the [[Eisenhower Trophy|Eisenhower Trophy World Team Championship]].

==Professional career==
Turning pro in 2011,<ref name=IMGProfile/> Lévy initially played on the [[Challenge Tour]] as an invited player in 2011 and 2012 before earning his [[European Tour]] playing rights at [[qualifying school]] for the 2013 season.

His first win of the European Tour came at the [[Volvo China Open]] in 2014, an event co-sanctioned with the [[OneAsia Tour]], where he shot a 19-under-par 269.<ref name=Kaplan>{{cite web |url=http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2014/04/29/fore/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140709114017/http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2014/04/29/fore/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=9 July 2014 |title=Fore |first=Ron |last=Kaplan |date=29 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/golf/27177241 |title=Alexander Levy wins China Open in Shenzhen by four shots |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=2014VCOscores>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2014/tournamentid=2014032/leaderboard/index.html |title=2014 Volvo China Open - Official Score |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> During the second round, Lévy shot a course record 62 at [[Genzon Golf Club]] giving him a four-stroke lead at the halfway point from which he was able to hold on to win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2014/tournamentid=2014032/news/newsid=221553.html |title=Levy keen to continue French renaissance |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Following this win Levy was named as [[2014 European Tour#Golfer of the Month|April 2014 European Tour Golfer of the Month]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2014/tournamentid=2014032/news/newsid=221947.html |title=Levy named Race to Dubai Golfer of the Month |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref>

His first appearance in a major championship was at the [[2014 PGA Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pga.com/pgachampionship/news/2014-pga-championship-field |title=2014 PGA Championship Field |publisher=[[PGA of America]] |accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, he claimed his second European Tour win at the [[Portugal Masters]] in an event which was shortened to 36 holes due to adverse weather conditions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/golf/29589217 |title=Portugal Masters: Alexander Levy wins rain-shortened event |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=12 October 2014}}</ref> With his win, he became the first French golfer to win more than once in the same season.<ref name=volvo>{{cite web |url=http://volvochinaopen.com/en/node/10529 |title=Alexander Levy – The Man With The Golden Touch |publisher=Volvo China Open |date=30 April 2017}}</ref>

In winning the 2016 [[Porsche European Open]] at [[Bad Griesbach]], Germany, at the age of 26 years and 55 days, he became the youngest Frenchman in history to win three European Tour titles.<ref name=volvo/><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.golfdigest.com/story/alexander-levy-delivers-an-instant-classic-club-twirl-in-euro-tour-win |title=Alexander Levy delivers an instant-classic club twirl in Euro Tour win |magazine=Golf Digest |first=Joel |last=Beall |date=25 September 2016}}</ref>

He again won the Volvo China Open in 2017, becoming the first two-time winner of the event in its 23-year history.<ref name=volvo/>

==Amateur wins (2)==
*2009 French Amateur Championship
*2010 French International Amateur Championship

